## Operators

### operator delete() {#a7df3c98b36215141b42b0a6ec782ddfa}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>void operator delete (void &#42; Ptr, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/mccontext">llvm::MCContext</a> &amp; C, size&#95;t)</>}
  labels = {["inline", "noexcept"]}>
Placement delete companion to the new above.

This operator is just a companion to the new above. There is no way of invoking it directly; see the new operator for more details. This operator is called implicitly by the compiler if a placement new expression using the MCContext throws in the object constructor.

Definition at line <a href="#l00883">883</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/mc/mccontext-h">MCContext.h</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

### operator new() {#ae8739ede42a4f9778b67d666086b9d96}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>void &#42; operator new (size&#95;t Bytes, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/mccontext">llvm::MCContext</a> &amp; C, size&#95;t Alignment=8)</>}
  labels = {["inline", "noexcept"]}>
Placement new for using the MCContext&#39;s allocator.

This placement form of operator new uses the MCContext&#39;s allocator for obtaining memory. It is a non-throwing new, which means that it returns null on error. (If that is what the allocator does. The current does, so if this ever changes, this operator will have to be changed, too.) Usage looks like this (assuming there&#39;s an MCContext &#39;Context&#39; in scope): 
<ProgramListing>

<CodeLine><Highlight kind="normal">// Default alignment (8)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<CodeLine><Highlight kind="normal">IntegerLiteral &#42;Ex = new (Context) IntegerLiteral(arguments);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<CodeLine><Highlight kind="normal">// Specific alignment</Highlight></CodeLine>
<CodeLine><Highlight kind="normal">IntegerLiteral &#42;Ex2 = new (Context, 4) IntegerLiteral(arguments);</Highlight></CodeLine>

</ProgramListing> Please note that you cannot use delete on the pointer; it must be deallocated using an explicit destructor call followed by <code>Context.Deallocate(Ptr)</code>.


<ParametersList title="Parameters">
<ParametersListItem name="Bytes">The number of bytes to allocate. Calculated by the compiler.</ParametersListItem>
<ParametersListItem name="C">The MCContext that provides the allocator.</ParametersListItem>
<ParametersListItem name="Alignment">The alignment of the allocated memory (if the underlying allocator supports it).</ParametersListItem>
</ParametersList>

<SectionUser title="Returns">
The allocated memory. Could be NULL.
</SectionUser>

Definition at line <a href="#l00873">873</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/mc/mccontext-h">MCContext.h</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

### operator new&#91;&#93;() {#a8002ed4c7e4b8a9a1177ec9fbd7826b3}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>void &#42; operator new&#91;&#93; (size&#95;t Bytes, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/mccontext">llvm::MCContext</a> &amp; C, size&#95;t Alignment=8)</>}
  labels = {["inline", "noexcept"]}>
This placement form of operator new&#91;&#93; uses the MCContext&#39;s allocator for obtaining memory.

It is a non-throwing new&#91;&#93;, which means that it returns null on error. Usage looks like this (assuming there&#39;s an MCContext &#39;Context&#39; in scope): 
<ProgramListing>

<CodeLine><Highlight kind="normal">// Default alignment (8)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<CodeLine><Highlight kind="normal">char &#42;data = new (Context) char&#91;10&#93;;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<CodeLine><Highlight kind="normal">// Specific alignment</Highlight></CodeLine>
<CodeLine><Highlight kind="normal">char &#42;data = new (Context, 4) char&#91;10&#93;;</Highlight></CodeLine>

</ProgramListing> Please note that you cannot use delete on the pointer; it must be deallocated using an explicit destructor call followed by <code>Context.Deallocate(Ptr)</code>.


<ParametersList title="Parameters">
<ParametersListItem name="Bytes">The number of bytes to allocate. Calculated by the compiler.</ParametersListItem>
<ParametersListItem name="C">The MCContext that provides the allocator.</ParametersListItem>
<ParametersListItem name="Alignment">The alignment of the allocated memory (if the underlying allocator supports it).</ParametersListItem>
</ParametersList>

<SectionUser title="Returns">
The allocated memory. Could be NULL.
</SectionUser>

Definition at line <a href="#l00906">906</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/mc/mccontext-h">MCContext.h</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

</SectionDefinition>

<Link id="l00849" /><CodeLine lineNumber="849"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// operator new and delete aren&#39;t allowed inside namespaces.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00850" /><CodeLine lineNumber="850"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// The throw specifications are mandated by the standard.</Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00851" /><CodeLine lineNumber="851"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Placement new for using the MCContext&#39;s allocator.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00852" /><CodeLine lineNumber="852"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00853" /><CodeLine lineNumber="853"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This placement form of operator new uses the MCContext&#39;s allocator for</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00854" /><CodeLine lineNumber="854"><Highlight kind="comment">/// obtaining memory. It is a non-throwing new, which means that it returns</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00855" /><CodeLine lineNumber="855"><Highlight kind="comment">/// null on error. (If that is what the allocator does. The current does, so if</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00856" /><CodeLine lineNumber="856"><Highlight kind="comment">/// this ever changes, this operator will have to be changed, too.)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00857" /><CodeLine lineNumber="857"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Usage looks like this (assuming there&#39;s an MCContext &#39;Context&#39; in scope):</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00858" /><CodeLine lineNumber="858"><Highlight kind="comment">/// \\code</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00859" /><CodeLine lineNumber="859"><Highlight kind="comment">/// // Default alignment (8)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00860" /><CodeLine lineNumber="860"><Highlight kind="comment">/// IntegerLiteral &#42;Ex = new (Context) IntegerLiteral(arguments);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00861" /><CodeLine lineNumber="861"><Highlight kind="comment">/// // Specific alignment</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00862" /><CodeLine lineNumber="862"><Highlight kind="comment">/// IntegerLiteral &#42;Ex2 = new (Context, 4) IntegerLiteral(arguments);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00863" /><CodeLine lineNumber="863"><Highlight kind="comment">/// \\endcode</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00864" /><CodeLine lineNumber="864"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Please note that you cannot use delete on the pointer; it must be</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00865" /><CodeLine lineNumber="865"><Highlight kind="comment">/// deallocated using an explicit destructor call followed by</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00866" /><CodeLine lineNumber="866"><Highlight kind="comment">/// \\c Context.Deallocate(Ptr).</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00867" /><CodeLine lineNumber="867"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00868" /><CodeLine lineNumber="868"><Highlight kind="comment">/// \\param Bytes The number of bytes to allocate. Calculated by the compiler.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00869" /><CodeLine lineNumber="869"><Highlight kind="comment">/// \\param C The MCContext that provides the allocator.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00870" /><CodeLine lineNumber="870"><Highlight kind="comment">/// \\param Alignment The alignment of the allocated memory (if the underlying</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00871" /><CodeLine lineNumber="871"><Highlight kind="comment">///                  allocator supports it).</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00872" /><CodeLine lineNumber="872"><Highlight kind="comment">/// \\return The allocated memory. Could be NULL.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00873" /><CodeLine lineNumber="873" lineLink="#ae8739ede42a4f9778b67d666086b9d96"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">inline</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordtype">void</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> &#42;</Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">operator</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">new</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">(</Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordtype">size&#95;t</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> Bytes, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/mccontext">llvm::MCContext</a> &amp;<a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/ir/builtingcs-cpp/#a1960c14773241d6a238d2db593abe552">C</a>,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00874" /><CodeLine lineNumber="874"><Highlight kind="normal">                          </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordtype">size&#95;t</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> Alignment = 8) </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">noexcept</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00875" /><CodeLine lineNumber="875"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">return</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/ir/builtingcs-cpp/#a1960c14773241d6a238d2db593abe552">C</a>.allocate(Bytes, Alignment);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00876" /><CodeLine lineNumber="876"><Highlight kind="normal">&#125;</Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00877" /><CodeLine lineNumber="877"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Placement delete companion to the new above.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00878" /><CodeLine lineNumber="878"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00879" /><CodeLine lineNumber="879"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This operator is just a companion to the new above. There is no way of</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00880" /><CodeLine lineNumber="880"><Highlight kind="comment">/// invoking it directly; see the new operator for more details. This operator</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00881" /><CodeLine lineNumber="881"><Highlight kind="comment">/// is called implicitly by the compiler if a placement new expression using</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00882" /><CodeLine lineNumber="882"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the MCContext throws in the object constructor.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00883" /><CodeLine lineNumber="883" lineLink="#a7df3c98b36215141b42b0a6ec782ddfa"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">inline</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordtype">void</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">operator</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">delete</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">(</Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordtype">void</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> &#42;<a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/analysis/targetlibraryinfo-cpp/#aca185e6d0e9f423dbb24440206454872a11dbf501abf829b3ab7049c2d3a8a053">Ptr</a>, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/mccontext">llvm::MCContext</a> &amp;<a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/ir/builtingcs-cpp/#a1960c14773241d6a238d2db593abe552">C</a>, size&#95;t) </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">noexcept</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
